Raw dev notes -- Building a Content Sync Pipeline: The Struggle with Large Files and CI

Okay, so this past week was all about getting the `halachot-orvishua` project off the ground. Basically, the idea is to build a reliable pipeline to pull down and manage content related to Jewish law (halachot) from a specific online source, `orvishua.net`. The main goal is to have an automated system that checks for new content, downloads it, and then notifies me (or others) about what's changed, especially which "mega-files" need to be re-uploaded to their final destination. It's about keeping a local, updated copy and making sure we know what's fresh.

This period was mostly about setting up the core infrastructure and figuring out the content flow. I started with the initial repo setup, getting a basic README in place with setup instructions and how to configure Gmail SMTP for notifications. A big early decision was to make this a "scripts-only repo," meaning the actual content itself wouldn't live in Git. Instead, it would be stored on Google Drive. This immediately led to some interesting challenges.

One of the first hurdles was the CI. My initial CI setup tried to download content, which was a no-go given the "scripts-only" decision and the size of the content. Had to fix that pretty quickly to a "detect-only" mode where the workflow doesn't try to pull down the actual content. That was a bit of a facepalm moment, realizing I'd set up CI to do something I explicitly didn't want Git to manage.

Then came the core logic: change detection and email notifications. I got the system to detect changes and, crucially, to specify *which* sources needed re-uploading and even *exactly which mega-files* were affected. This was a big win, as it's the whole point of the project – knowing what's new and what needs attention.

The content management strategy evolved quite a bit. Initially, it was all about keeping content out of Git. But then I realized I needed *some* representation of the output in Git for tracking purposes, so I implemented syncing the output to a git-tracked directory. This felt like a compromise, but a necessary one. Later, I did a big reorganization, moving all scripts into a `scripts/` directory and all content (or at least the *output* content that *is* tracked) into a `content/` directory, cleaning up the project root. This felt much better, aligning with a pattern I've seen work well in other projects, using `new_content/` and a `content_index.json` to manage things more systematically. It's a constant battle between "keep it simple" and "make it robust for large, dynamic data."

Finally, I got a successful sync run, pulling down 2 new Q&A items and confirming 0 new articles from `orvishua.net`. That was a satisfying little green checkmark.

Honestly, the hardest part was wrestling with the content strategy. The initial thought of "scripts-only, content on Drive" seemed clean, but then the practicalities of CI, tracking changes, and needing *some* versioned output meant constantly re-evaluating. It felt like I was building the plane while flying it, making decisions, seeing them break, and then refactoring. The "mega-files" aspect really drove home that Git isn't always the right tool for *all* data, but you still need a way to track *metadata* about that data. It was a good reminder that architectural decisions are rarely one-and-done; they evolve as you understand the problem space better. Also, line endings. Always line endings. Had to add `.gitattributes` and normalize them to LF, because of course.

Overall, it felt good to get the core loop working. It's a small project, but it touches on some fundamental data management and automation principles. It's a step towards building more reliable, self-maintaining systems, which is always a growth area for me.

Next up: Refine the notification content and potentially add more robust error handling.
